result.execSummary:
The defendant Michael J Henke was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Disorderly Conduct [Modifiers: Domestic Abuse, Repeater], a class B misdemeanor, Wisconsin Statutes 947.01(1).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Exhibits 1-3
Preliminary

9:12 Defendant Michael J Henke in court with attorney Gary J. Kryshak.  Craig Lambert appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Court convenes without presence of jury. Attorney Lambert states that parties stipulate to defendant having 14 prior convictions and victim has one.
Attorney Kryshak states that they wish Court to decide bail jumping charge. Attorney Lambert objects to that. Criminal complaint on 14CF89 is discussed and whether it needs to be redacted or if the jury can see it. Court orders that criminal complaint be redacted. There is no waiver of right to jury trial on count 1. There are no other stipulations. Court questions defendant regarding his prior criminal convictions.
9:27 Jurors are brought into courtroom and sworn. Twenty jurors are called to box.
9:33 Court reads charges and begins voir dire. Juror #11 is struck for cause.
9:41 Attorney Lambert does voir dire. 
10:03 Attorney Kryshak does voir dire. Juror #19 is struck for cause.
10:11 Strikes are made.
10:21 Twelve jurors are sworn.
10:23 Attorney Lambert gives opening statement.
10:28 Attorney Kryshak gives opening statement.
10:37 Jurors in recess. Sidebar is put on the record.
10:39 Court in recess.
10:58 Court reconvenes without presence of jury. Attorney Lambert states that he has redacted criminal complaint. Attorney Kryshak states that the complaint is fine as redacted. Attorney Lambert asks court to take judicial notice that the defendant was charged with a felony that he was out on bond and that the bond was in effect on 7/6/14. Attorney Kryshak does not object. Court takes judicial notice. Exhibits #1 & 2 are marked. Attorney Kryshak moves to sequester witnesses. Granted. Officer may remain in courtroom.
11:01 Jurors are brought into courtroom. Attorney Lambert asks Court take judicial notice of 14CF89. Attorney Kryshak does not object. Court takes judicial notice. Exhibits #1 & 2 are received.
11:03 Anna Heroldt is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Lambert. She states that the defendant is her ex-boyfriend. They have a child together. The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom. On 7/6/14, she was living with defendant in Nekoosa, Wood County, in a boyfriend/girlfriend relationship. She states she has been convicted of one crime. She testifies as to the incident that occurred on 7/6/14 at their residence. She feels that defendant may have been having a relationship with someone else. She confronted him about it. Defendant became agitated and aggressive. She testifies that the defendant grabbed her by the neck and dragged her in the hallway and pushed her on the bed. Defendant held her head facedown on the bed and she was not able to breathe for a time and it was painful on her neck. After he let her up, she went to the bathroom to take a bath and defendant came in and apologized to her. Defendant then wanted to have sex. She told him that she did not want to. But he persisted. She felt like she did not have a choice and they had sex. She went to the Family Center the next day. She reported the incident to the Nekoosa Police Department. Exhibit #3 is marked and reviewed with witness. She enforced the 72-hour no contact.
11:35 Court in recess.
12:55 Court reconvenes without presence of jury. Defendant wishes to plead to charges.
1:30 Jurors are brought into the courtroom and dismissed.

9:06 Defendant Michael J Henke in court with attorney Gary J. Kryshak.  Kelly A. Lehn appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Jason Wilson is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Lehn. He is an officer with the Nekoosa Police Department. On 7/6/14, he spoke to A.H. who wanted to report a domestic abuse incident that had occurred in the City of Nekoosa. She stated that she confronted the defendant about something she was upset about and he became aggressive and pushed her down on the bed. He later questioned defendant regarding the incident. The witness identifies the defendant in the courtroom. Attorney Kryshak cross-examines witness. 
Attorney Lehn asks Court to take judical notice of Wood County case 14CF89, a felony case that defendant was on bond. Court takes judical notice.
Ross Radtke is sworn as a witness and questioned by Attorney Lehn. He is an officer with the Wisconsin Rapids Police Department. On 8/7/14, he was dispatched to a residence in the City of Wisconsin Rapids. L.H. indicated that he was sleeping and he heard someone entering his residence and the saw defendant standing in his doorway with a knife demanding to speak to A.H. Attorney Kryshak stipulates that Michael Henke is the person in the courtroom. Attorney Kryshak cross-examines witness. Court also takes judicial notice of Wood County case 14CF89 for this charge.
Court finds probable cause that a felony was committed and the defendant committed them. Bound over for further proceedings. Bond is continued.  Pre-trial conference scheduled for October 24, 2014 at 10:00 am.
Preliminary hearing and Arraignment on September 17, 2014 at 09:00 am.
